hey uncover that white religious fervor correlates to notions of perceived white loss and perceived black progress. In discussions ranging from the Constitution to the Charlottesville riots and the evangelical Christian community's uncritical support for Trump, this collection argues that it is not economics but religion and race that stand as the primary motivating factors for the rise of white rage and white supremacist sentiment in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEthnische Identität. 0aNationalismus. 0aRacismzUnited States. 0aRight-wing extremistszUnited States. 0aWhite nationalismzUnited States. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited States. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxReligion. 4aPolitics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh1 aEasterling, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnard, Kimberly R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaulk, Danae M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinley, Stephen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFones-Wolf, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFones-Wolf, Ken, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Biko Mandela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHarris, Brenda G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHills, Darrius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/